snippet.textDisplay: Those defending Isiah Thomas and saying things like he didn't lie etc...It's not that he told a lie, it's the fact he left out some important details. Which Scottie Pippen touched on later. The Bulls were very young, immature and up and coming.  Phil Jackson didn't become coach until 1989. They were in the building process. Michael Jordan was young and didn't have much help. Scottie Pippen was a rookie in 87-88. Scottie really didn't become the all star caliber Scottie Pippen we all know, until the early 90s and that is when the Bulls swept the Detroit Pistons and never looked back from there. The Bulls improved and got better each year with experience, as they were in their primes. Not to mention, they were without Toni Kukoc, Ron Harper and Dennis Rodman because Rodman was on the Pistons then. We all know the best Chicago Bulls team was the late 90s Bulls with the addition of Dennis Rodman, Toni Kukoc, Ron Harper, Steve Kerr, Luc Longley etc....Also every team has to go through trials and tribulations to become great and yes, the Detroit Pistons were that trial/ building block that made the Bulls better and helped them grow and mature before they propelled unto greatness becoming the greatest team and dynasty of all time!!

snippet.textDisplay: First take, a polite request from a fellow basketball player and fan. Please take Max off this show when you have serious guests. Not only is he annoyingly disrespectful to people that have actually been through that fire of not only playing NBA basketball, but playing Jordan, he clearly speaks with the lack of understanding inherent in one who has only watched but never competitively played the game at high level. His understanding of the game is inadequate to put him on the same show with people that not only played in the best league in the world, but were all time greats and actually had to defend Jordan. How do you think your opinion on basketball, on playing against greats, on stopping greats, holds more weight than Isiah Thomas? How do you really think you can tell him, who actually had to do it for years, what it was like guarding Jordan and Pippen? And you don't see something wrong with that? My friend, when Isiah speaks, you should be listening. So First Take, please, for crying out loud, leave Max Kellerman for hypothetical conversations about who would win , Jordan's Bulls vs Kobe's Lakers. That's where his kind of conjecture belongs. But when you have a chance to sit and talk with a special talent, an individual with the basketball clarity and understanding of Isiah Thomas, a member of the last team to really beat Jordan, please bring us people who deserve to sit at the table and have that conversation. Otherwise, you're simply robbing us, as fans of the game who want to listen to real basketball insight.

snippet.textDisplay:
Zeke is right but he's also wrong.
Pistons, from 87/88 until 92/93 had a 29-23 advantage over the Bulls in all of the regular and post season matchups. BUT, Zeke is sitting there making out as if he was the only great player on that team while Jordan had Scottie 'a top 50 player of all time'. Dude, did you forget who Dennis Rodman is? Sure he didn't make that top 50 list but nobody now is denying that he is a top 50 player of all time. The dude is, at worst, a top 3 rebounder of all time, quite possibly THE best ever while also being one of the all time great defenders (2x DPOY) and a 5 time NBA champion. Rodman being overlooked in these discussions is a classic case of PPG tunnel vision. Just because he didn't score people assume he wasn't great. Rubbish.
Anyway, the discussion was originally 'MJ didn't win until Pippen became an ALL STAR', it wasn't about being a top 50 player of all time. Zeke not only had 2 time All Star Dennis Rodman, he had multiple All Star Joe Dumars (career 6x AS), 4 time All Star Bill Laimbeer as well as 3 x All Star Mark Aguirre. That team was stacked with All Stars but Zeke is out here trying to convince everyone he was the only star on that team. Not the case I'm afraid.
